<seg id="1042">If a picture is rendered with only one beam per pixel, several errors can occur. these images often have a moiré pattern or tier effects in curves and lines, and sometimes details are not displayed if they are smaller than a pixel. this effect is called aliasing.</seg>
<seg id="1043">& Povray; uses a technique called anti-aliasing to reduce the impact of these errors. generally, pictures with this property look better.</seg>
<seg id="1044">If you switch on anti-aliasing, calculates and connects & Povray; more than one beam per pixel. this technique is super sampling.</seg>
<seg id="1045">& Povray; supports two methods of super sampling. as standard is an adaptive, non-recursive method; adaptive, because the super sampling gets the adjacent pixels with one. the second method is adaptive-recursive; recursive because every pixel is always further divided and adapted because the recursion depth depends on the calculated colours.</seg>
<seg id="1046">If you choose the first method, POV-Ray uses a beam per pixel. if the difference between the color values to the neighbouring pixels exceeds the given threshold, then both pixels are processed by tracking a certain additional number of pixels with super sampling. if you set the depth value to 4, a grid of 4x4 is calculated, with a depth of 5 then 5x5 (25) additional rays per pixel.</seg>
<seg id="1047">The difference between two pixels is calculated as follows: r 1, g 1 and b 1 are the values for red, green and blue of the first pixel, r 2, g 2 and b 2 are the values for red, green and blue of the second pixel.</seg>
<seg id="1048">Diff = abs (r 1 -r 2) + abs (g 1 -g 2) + abs (b 1 -b 2)</seg>
<seg id="1049">The recursive method starts with 4 rays per pixel. if the difference between the color values exceeds the specified threshold, then the pixel is divided into 4 subpixels that are individually followed and checked for further subdivision. the maximum depth of the recursion can be adjusted with the depth value.</seg>
